# Engineering Hard Rules

These apply to all UMO TypeScript codebases.

## Type safety

- No `any` — use `unknown` with type guards, or explicit types
- Explicit return types on all exported functions
- Strict mode enabled (`strict: true` in tsconfig)

## Error handling

- No `throw new Error()` in new code — use typed error returns (Effect errors, Result types, or error unions)
- Never swallow errors silently — always log or propagate
- CLI scripts are exempt from typed-error requirement (they may throw for user-facing output)

## Logging

- No `console.log`, `console.error`, `console.warn` in committed code
- Use structured logging (Effect Logger, pino, or the project's chosen logger)
- Never log sensitive data (PII, tokens, passwords, API keys)

## Config

- No `process.env` in business logic — use config abstraction
- Secrets come from Vault or env, never hardcoded

## Service communication

- No raw `fetch()` for internal service-to-service calls — use typed clients (ConnectRPC, SDK)
- REST is acceptable only for: OAuth/OIDC, AI SDK chat, MCP HTTP transport

## Database

- One database per service (not schema isolation)
- Drizzle ORM only — no Prisma, no Knex, no raw SQL strings with concatenation
- Never hand-edit migration files — use the migration generator
